RT  An aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase that specifically activates pyrrolysine.
RA  Polycarpo C, Ambrogelly A, Bérubé A, Winbush SM, McCloskey JA, Crain
RA  PF, Wood JL, Söll D;
RL  Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2004;101:12450-12454.
RN  [2]
RM  17204561
RT  A natural genetic code expansion cassette enables transmissible
RT  biosynthesis and genetic encoding of pyrrolysine.
RA  Longstaff DG, Larue RC, Faust JE, Mahapatra A, Zhang L, Green-Church
RA  KB, Krzycki JA;
RL  Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2007;104:1021-1026.
CC  In methanogens, methylamine methyltransferases have an in-frame TAG
CC  codon that is translated with a lysine amide-linked to
CC  (4R,5R)-4-substituted-pyrroline-5-carboxylate. This residue is called
CC  pyrrolysine, and is considered the 22nd amino acid, where
CC  selenocysteine is the 21st. Pyrrrolysine occurs also in
CC  Desulfitobacterium hafniense and related species; proteins in which
CC  pyrrolysine occurs are not necessarily homologous to each other. A
CC  three-gene cassette, pylBCD, produces the pyrrolysine prior to its
CC  attachment to its cognate tRNA.
**  >PylT pyrrolyinse tRNA
**  GGGAACCTGATCATGTAGATCGAATGGACTCTAAATCCGTTTAGCCGGGTTAGATTCCCG
**  GGGTTTCCGCCA So far, restricted among complete genomes to two species
**  Methanosarcina. DHH.  Three different non-homologous enzymes all with
**  PyL take methyl group from trimethyl (see PF06253), dimethyl, and
**  monomethylamine (PF05369) (sequentially) in Methanosarcina.
